AB  - This paper investigates the relative technical efficiency of firms operating under different competitive pressures. Using observations from multational firms in Taiwan's electronics industry, we find that firms are constrained to export all their products and thus to compete in the world markets (namely, the export-oriented) tend to be more efficient than those allowed to sell their products in the protected local markets (namely, the import-substitution-oriented). Depending on the model specification, the export-oriented firms are 6% to 11% closer to the production frontier than the import-substitution-oriented firms.
