AB  - Using the Chenery-Syrquin models of structural change, and internationally comparable data on GDP per capita and shares of consumption, investment and government spending for the 1960s and the 1970s, a study is conducted of changes in the structure of domestic absorption that accompany economic growth. Relative to the conventional data, ‘real’ data indicate the fall in the share of consumption to be somewhat lower and the rise in the share of investment to be larger, as GDP per capita rises. The share of government is observed to decline, although most previous studies indicate an increase in government share with economic growth.
